{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Beach at Pourville.jpg | alt=See adjacent text. | image_size=320px | title=Beach in Pourville | artist=[[Claude Monet]] | year= 1882 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[canvas]] | height_metric= | width_metric= | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Poland]] | museum=[[National Museum, Poznań]] }}
'''''Beach in Pourville''''' (title in French: ''La plage à Pourville, soleil couchant'') is a painting by [[France|French]] artist [[Claude Monet]].<ref name="BBC">{{citation | title = Stolen Monet painting recovered in Poland| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/arts_and_culture/8461814.stm | publisher = BBC News | date = 15 January 2010}}.</ref> It is one of an 1882 series of oil-on-canvas works by Monet in the small seaside resort of Pourville-sur-Mer (now part of the [[Communes of France|''commune'']] of [[Hautot-sur-Mer]]), near [[Dieppe, Seine-Maritime|Dieppe]] in northern France. Monet is considered one of the most important members of the group of painters identified as the [[Impressionist]]s. The painting was bought by the [[National Museum, Poznań]], [[Poland]] in 1906 and exhibited in the display of their collection.<ref name="PolskieRadio">{{citation | title = Monet back in Poznan Museum | url = http://www.thenews.pl/national/artykul123816_monet-back-in-poznan-museum.html | publisher = Polskie Radio | date = 16 January 2010}}.</ref>
==Theft and recovery== The painting [[art theft|was stolen]] from the Poznań National Museum in September 2000.<ref name="BBC"/> It was cut out of its frame and replaced with a copy, which had been painted on cardboard. At the time, the painting was valued at more than [[United States dollar|$]]1&nbsp;million,<ref name="BBC"/><ref name="PolskieRadio"/> and was the only painting by Monet on public display in Poland.<ref name="AFP">{{citation | title = Poland's stolen Monet found, suspect arrested | url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5geFmRhYbBgXNCMaE_eu7ltw5mn7w | publisher = Agence France Presse}}.</ref> The theft was discovered on 19&nbsp;September 2000, and police searched for a man who had been seen making sketches of paintings in the museum two days earlier.<ref name="BBC"/>
The painting was recovered on 12 January 2010.<ref name="BBC"/><ref name="PolskieRadio"/><ref name="Sofia">{{citation | title = Stolen Monet recovered in Poland| url = http://www.sofiaecho.com/2010/01/15/843015_stolen-monet-recovered-in-poland | publisher = Sofia Echo | date = 15 January 2010}}.</ref> Police also arrested a 41-year-old man in the southern Polish city of [[Olkusz]],<ref name="BBC"/> whom they believe to be the painter of the copy used in the robbery.<ref name="AFP"/> The suspect was traced through fingerprints and other evidence left at the site of the theft.<ref name="PA">{{citation | title = Stolen Monet painting recovered| url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5hYKIj54PEEnxudCUwH8hCo_0yIlw | publisher = Press Association | date = 13 January 2010}}.</ref>
